All the old fashioned puddings that we all used to like.

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:14.100
Did you eat in the canteen often?

00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:17.100
I used to go there every day.

00:15:17.100 --> 00:15:20.100
Was it reasonable?

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:24.100
Yes, it was subsidised.

00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:32.100
We used to work Saturday mornings when I first started there.

00:15:32.100 --> 00:15:39.100
You used to get one Saturday morning off in three.

00:15:39.100 --> 00:15:42.100
That was a bit of a bind.

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:45.100
How many hours a week did you work then?

00:15:45.100 --> 00:15:51.100
Eight to five.

00:15:51.100 --> 00:16:01.100
Nine to five, five days a week and then nine to twelve on Saturday.

00:16:01.100 --> 00:16:05.100
I'd say eight hours a day.

00:16:05.100 --> 00:16:08.100
Did you have an hour for lunch?

00:16:08.100 --> 00:16:09.100
Yes.

00:16:09.100 --> 00:16:11.100
They probably didn't count that.

00:16:11.100 --> 00:16:12.100
No, probably.

00:16:12.100 --> 00:16:14.100
So that's 38 hours then.

00:16:14.100 --> 00:16:16.100
Yes.

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:19.100
What about afternoon break?

00:16:19.100 --> 00:16:23.100
We just made something in the lab again.

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:31.100
Take me through work then.

00:16:31.100 --> 00:16:32.100
What would you do?

00:16:32.100 --> 00:16:35.100
You said you had these samples coming in.

00:16:35.100 --> 00:16:38.100
Yes, they used to bring those up from...

00:16:38.100 --> 00:16:44.100
There was a part of the lab downstairs where they prepared the steel samples.

00:16:44.100 --> 00:16:47.100
Because it wouldn't be big lumps of steel.

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:52.100
They used to mill, shave it, like shavings off it.

00:16:52.100 --> 00:16:58.100
The first thing to do was weigh out all these different samples.

00:16:58.100 --> 00:17:00.100
Very often they'd be 60.

00:17:00.100 --> 00:17:04.100
The balances we had were not electronic.

00:17:04.100 --> 00:17:08.100
They were the old fashioned swing balances.

00:17:08.100 --> 00:17:11.100
Some people had it off to a fine art.

00:17:11.100 --> 00:17:13.100
They were really quick.

00:17:13.100 --> 00:17:18.100
Then you'd go through the whole process of the analysis.

00:17:18.100 --> 00:17:21.100
Get the results and everything.

00:17:21.100 --> 00:17:25.100
There were a couple of people employed there.

00:17:25.100 --> 00:17:28.100
They used to wash up all the apparatus.

00:17:28.100 --> 00:17:32.100
Then at 11 o'clock usually another lot came in.

00:17:32.100 --> 00:17:34.100
We'd started all again.

00:17:34.100 --> 00:17:37.100
Then you'd get another lot in the afternoon.

00:17:37.100 --> 00:17:40.100
It was quite busy.

00:17:40.100 --> 00:17:43.100
Some days were worse than others.

00:17:43.100 --> 00:17:53.100
I can remember somebody saying once that there was a problem with one of the samples that we had analysed.

00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:59.100
Very often we'd have to go back and do it again and check it and make sure.

00:17:59.100 --> 00:18:04.100
This one sample, we said, it's exactly the same as it was before.

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:06.100
Oh, crumbs.

00:18:06.100 --> 00:18:08.100
The ship's on its way to Malaya.

00:18:08.100 --> 00:18:10.100
Things like that.

00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:12.100
Which we all thought was a hoot.

00:18:12.100 --> 00:18:16.100
So what were you analysing for?

00:18:16.100 --> 00:18:24.100
We used to do phosphorus, manganese, silicon, carbon, sulphur.

00:18:24.100 --> 00:18:28.100
I'm sure there were a few others I've missed out.

00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:30.100
Lead.

00:18:30.100 --> 00:18:33.100
We used to do quite a few different things.

00:18:33.100 --> 00:18:36.100
Quite a few elements you should be looking for.

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:44.100
Different types of steel have different specifications of the elements that have to be in them.

00:18:44.100 --> 00:18:48.100
We used to do, and it's the one thing I always remember.

00:18:48.100 --> 00:18:53.100
We used to analyse one steel called GK60.

00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:56.100
That was concrete reinforcing rods.

00:18:56.100 --> 00:19:02.100
Whenever I see a building going up with concrete rods, I think, I wonder if that's GK60.

00:19:02.100 --> 00:19:05.100
Not anymore, I shouldn't think.

00:19:05.100 --> 00:19:11.100
But you didn't, they weren't making the steel, so you were analysing somebody else's steel?

00:19:11.100 --> 00:19:15.100
Yes, it was what they were actually sending out.

00:19:15.100 --> 00:19:23.100
They didn't actually make it there, so whether they ever added any elements,

00:19:23.100 --> 00:19:31.100
because it would be hot in the furnaces, I suppose, when they rolled it.

00:19:31.100 --> 00:19:36.100
So whether they ever added any elements there, I don't know.

00:19:36.100 --> 00:19:41.100
You know, sort of things like manganese and all the rest of it, I'm not sure.

00:19:41.100 --> 00:19:49.100
Or do you think they were maybe as well providing a service for the place that made the steel?

00:19:49.100 --> 00:19:53.100
Yes, perhaps, yeah. I'm not really sure.

00:19:53.100 --> 00:19:57.100
Because you didn't make it, I was wondering why.

00:19:57.100 --> 00:20:00.100
I don't think they made it there.

00:20:00.100 --> 00:20:08.100
I've got a friend's son who works, well, of course it comes under Salson now, it's a Spanish company.

00:20:08.100 --> 00:20:12.100
But I could easily ask Rita's husband worked there.

00:20:12.100 --> 00:20:17.100
He worked downstairs, I talked to him the other night about it.

00:20:17.100 --> 00:20:24.100
So how did you hear about the work, by the way? Why did you go for a job there specifically?

00:20:24.100 --> 00:20:31.100
Because of my friend in staff wages, she said to me, there's a job coming up in the lab.

00:20:31.100 --> 00:20:35.100
So that was how we went there.

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:40.100
What did you have to wear in the lab?

00:20:40.100 --> 00:20:46.100
We used to wear white coats. It was so hot there.

00:20:46.100 --> 00:20:51.100
We used to strip off to our underwear and put the white coats on,

00:20:51.100 --> 00:20:54.100
but very often they were covered in holes anyway.

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:58.100
So we used to wrap them around, and hide the holes.

00:20:58.100 --> 00:21:03.100
We didn't wear stockings because you'd drop acid on them.

00:21:03.100 --> 00:21:11.100
So we all wore sand draws, flip-flops sandals, those sort of things, barefoot, bare legs.

00:21:11.100 --> 00:21:17.100
We used to go across to the canteen like that, even when there was snow on the ground.

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:20.100
No wonder we all had bad bags.

00:21:20.100 --> 00:21:26.100
So you'd splash acid on your legs rather than your stockings?

00:21:26.100 --> 00:21:29.100
Yeah, we'd wear them quite long.

00:21:29.100 --> 00:21:33.100
Because you'd wash it off your legs.

00:21:33.100 --> 00:21:43.100
I think we didn't take the overalls home to wash. They were done by GKN.

00:21:43.100 --> 00:21:45.100
So were they provided by GKN?

00:21:45.100 --> 00:21:46.100
Yes.

00:21:46.100 --> 00:21:50.100
Were they cotton or were they nylon?

00:21:50.100 --> 00:21:53.100
They were cotton, thick cotton.

00:21:53.100 --> 00:21:55.100
Which was better in the beginning.

00:21:55.100 --> 00:22:01.100
Yes, because with the heat in there, nylon would have been awful.

00:22:01.100 --> 00:22:04.100
Why was it so hot in there?

00:22:04.100 --> 00:22:11.100
What they had there was four huge hot plates.

00:22:11.100 --> 00:22:14.100
There were two back-to-back.

00:22:14.100 --> 00:22:20.100
They were in the middle of the lab and there were extractive fans above them.

00:22:20.100 --> 00:22:23.100
It really did get very hot.

00:22:23.100 --> 00:22:25.100
So you had to heat?

00:22:25.100 --> 00:22:33.100
Yes. What we used to do, for I think nearly most of the analyses,

00:22:33.100 --> 00:22:36.100
you dissolved the steel in acid first.

00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:43.100
Then that's when you could add all the different chemicals

00:22:43.100 --> 00:22:48.100
to show up whatever you were looking for.

00:22:48.100 --> 00:22:57.100
If you did manganese, it was all done by colour spectrometry then.

00:22:57.100 --> 00:23:02.100
I think manganese was a sort of purpley colour as well, as I remember.

00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:08.100
We had instruments that would read the colour.

00:23:08.100 --> 00:23:14.100
We did do a couple of analyses that were carbon and sulphur,

00:23:14.100 --> 00:23:19.100
where you burned the steel in a little furnace.

00:23:19.100 --> 00:23:23.100
You'd put it in little boats.

00:23:23.100 --> 00:23:26.100
With the carbon one, the carbon would burn off.

00:23:26.100 --> 00:23:30.100
They'd be passing oxygen over it, so you'd get carbon dioxide,

00:23:30.100 --> 00:23:35.100
which would then get dried through, I think it was sulphuric acid,

00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:40.100
into, I can't remember what the blooming stuff was,

00:23:40.100 --> 00:23:44.100
it used to get absorbed into.

00:23:44.100 --> 00:23:47.100
You would weigh these, and that's what I'm doing there,

00:23:47.100 --> 00:23:57.100
you would weigh these things to find out how much carbon the steel contained.

00:23:57.100 --> 00:23:59.100
That's what you're doing in the photograph?

00:23:59.100 --> 00:24:03.100
Yes, I was doing that there.

00:24:03.100 --> 00:24:10.100
Apart from these overalls, cotton, were you given any protective clothing?

00:24:10.100 --> 00:24:14.100
Rubber gloves.

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:18.100
I'd get dermatitis from rubber gloves.

00:24:18.100 --> 00:24:20.100
I had it really bad when I was there.

00:24:20.100 --> 00:24:25.100
I didn't know I was going to get the problem.

00:24:25.100 --> 00:24:31.100
They were rubber gloves, and you can get them with a flock lining now.

00:24:31.100 --> 00:24:33.100
They weren't like that.

00:24:33.100 --> 00:24:35.100
They were just rubber.

00:24:35.100 --> 00:24:36.100
Oh, god, it was all...

00:24:36.100 --> 00:24:40.100
Oh, excuse me.

00:24:40.100 --> 00:24:43.100
So you were saying about the rubber gloves?

00:24:43.100 --> 00:24:45.100
Yes.

00:24:45.100 --> 00:24:47.100
Well, it's a common problem.

00:24:47.100 --> 00:24:49.100
Lots of people get it.

00:24:49.100 --> 00:24:54.100
My mother always had a problem, and my dad and my brother does as well.

00:24:54.100 --> 00:24:59.100
So I bought some white cotton gloves in boots of chemists,

00:24:59.100 --> 00:25:01.100
and I used to put them inside.

00:25:01.100 --> 00:25:06.100
Otherwise, I'd have had to give it up, because it was quite bad.

00:25:06.100 --> 00:25:09.100
What about masks or anything?

00:25:09.100 --> 00:25:11.100
Were you protected from fumes?

00:25:11.100 --> 00:25:12.100
No.

00:25:12.100 --> 00:25:14.100
Were the fumes coming off the...

00:25:14.100 --> 00:25:19.100
Yes, but because you put these samples on a hot plate

00:25:19.100 --> 00:25:22.100
that was underneath an extractor fan,

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:25.100
the fumes would be taken away.

00:25:25.100 --> 00:25:31.100
But they used to get a bit hairy there sometimes.

00:25:31.100 --> 00:25:34.100
And no protective footwear either?

00:25:34.100 --> 00:25:36.100
No.

00:25:36.100 --> 00:25:39.100
No, it was a lot different then.

00:25:39.100 --> 00:25:43.100
So do you think the work was dangerous in any way?

00:25:43.100 --> 00:25:46.100
Yes, it was.

