Yes, they closed the place down.

00:47:01.640 --> 00:47:09.640
Whatever, like the nail factory would close, the rod mill and all the rest of them,

00:47:09.640 --> 00:47:12.640
I can't remember what they all were.

00:47:12.640 --> 00:47:14.640
But no, that used to close down.

00:47:14.640 --> 00:47:18.640
And bank holidays work? Did you have paid bank holidays this Christmas?

00:47:18.640 --> 00:47:22.640
Yes, but we always worked Good Friday.

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:25.640
Good Friday isn't a bank holiday.

00:47:25.640 --> 00:47:29.640
Ah, but the bank closes, doesn't it? The banks close.

00:47:29.640 --> 00:47:31.640
Well, it's not an official bank holiday.

00:47:31.640 --> 00:47:34.640
Ah, right, but this was back in the 50s.

00:47:34.640 --> 00:47:38.640
Yes, but it's still not an official bank holiday, Good Friday.

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:41.640
All right. Ah, yes.

00:47:41.640 --> 00:47:46.640
Because there wouldn't be many buses then.

00:47:46.640 --> 00:47:51.640
And I can remember I used to catch a very early bus from Fairwater and get to town.

00:47:51.640 --> 00:47:57.640
And it would be something like three-quarters of an hour wait for the works bus.

00:47:57.640 --> 00:48:00.640
So I used to walk. Lots of people did.

00:48:00.640 --> 00:48:05.640
We'd walk all down Tyndall Street and up Eastmarsh Road.

00:48:05.640 --> 00:48:09.640
And I think of it now, I thought, we must have been mad.

00:48:09.640 --> 00:48:14.640
Yes. How long did it take you to get to work?

00:48:14.640 --> 00:48:17.640
On the bus. On the bus.

00:48:17.640 --> 00:48:20.640
When did you leave in the morning? Because if you...

00:48:20.640 --> 00:48:24.640
Yes. Did I used to... I'm trying to remember which bus I used to catch.

00:48:24.640 --> 00:48:28.640
I probably used to catch one about seven minutes to eight.

00:48:28.640 --> 00:48:32.640
There was always a bus at seven minutes to eight and I used it for years,

00:48:32.640 --> 00:48:35.640
I think, when I was in school as well.

00:48:35.640 --> 00:48:42.640
And then you'd get into Cardiff, you know, by the Central Station there.

00:48:42.640 --> 00:48:47.640
And the thing was you didn't want to miss the works bus.

00:48:47.640 --> 00:48:50.640
And that would go about twenty to nine.

00:48:50.640 --> 00:48:53.640
I think there was another one then at quarter to nine.

00:48:53.640 --> 00:48:58.640
They were Cardiff City buses, you know, just the double-deckers.

00:48:58.640 --> 00:49:05.640
I think there was a conductor on them and also somebody from the company,

00:49:05.640 --> 00:49:12.640
you know, would be standing there with the bus conductor,

00:49:12.640 --> 00:49:15.640
making sure everybody was behaving.

00:49:19.640 --> 00:49:22.640
So it took you a while to get to work then? Yes, yes.

00:49:22.640 --> 00:49:26.640
Yes, the same as I suppose things are today.

00:49:26.640 --> 00:49:30.640
It takes longer if you have to wait, you know,

00:49:30.640 --> 00:49:34.640
if you have to catch a couple of different buses or trains

00:49:34.640 --> 00:49:36.640
and you've got to wait in between.

00:49:36.640 --> 00:49:40.640
So then it does take a bit longer.

00:49:40.640 --> 00:49:43.640
You said your friends worked in the office.

00:49:43.640 --> 00:49:47.640
How many people worked in the offices, Jean, did you know?

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:52.640
There were quite a lot there because they had quite a few different divisions.

00:49:52.640 --> 00:49:56.640
I mean, she would know because she used to do the wages.

00:49:56.640 --> 00:50:02.640
And because they had a sales section,

00:50:02.640 --> 00:50:10.640
they had another section that there were girls there that did the punch cards.

00:50:10.640 --> 00:50:16.640
There would be a typing pool and there was a drawing office, you know,

00:50:16.640 --> 00:50:22.640
and I think probably like lots of factories that were manufacturing to sell,

00:50:22.640 --> 00:50:27.640
they would probably all have the same sort of departments.

00:50:27.640 --> 00:50:31.640
But there was quite a lot of people work there.

00:50:31.640 --> 00:50:37.640
So what about the factory floor? Did any women work on the factory floor?

00:50:37.640 --> 00:50:43.640
I don't think so. I never came across any. No.

00:50:44.640 --> 00:50:47.640
Was that really heavy work on the floor, do you think?

00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:53.640
I think it may well have been, yes.

00:50:53.640 --> 00:51:01.640
Yes, because, you know, I can remember sort of walking past one of the buildings

00:51:01.640 --> 00:51:06.640
and I can't remember what it was called, whether it was the cold roll mill or something like this.

00:51:06.640 --> 00:51:16.640
I saw this sort of steel coming out of the little furnace, wherever it was coming from,

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:22.640
and it was sort of big thick rods, you know, and that was going straight,

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:27.640
not like on a curved track like the one where I saw it come off.

00:51:27.640 --> 00:51:33.640
But, you know, it did look pretty heavy work.

00:51:33.640 --> 00:51:36.640
Where did you see it come off again?

00:51:36.640 --> 00:51:39.640
Oh, just walking past. Oh, when it came off?

00:51:39.640 --> 00:51:44.640
Oh, that was over in Trimorfer Works, which was also part of Gaskin and Etelfolds.

00:51:44.640 --> 00:51:46.640
I think that was the rod mill.

00:51:46.640 --> 00:51:48.640
Why had you gone over there?

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:52.640
Oh, they just thought they would show us, you know,

00:51:52.640 --> 00:51:56.640
that we'd probably analyse some steel that they were producing there,

00:51:56.640 --> 00:52:01.640
and they just thought they would, you know, take some of us over

00:52:01.640 --> 00:52:06.640
so that we could see how the other half was living, really.

00:52:06.640 --> 00:52:10.640
But that was interesting, I must admit, and frightening.

00:52:10.640 --> 00:52:18.640
Yes. Can you describe the works, the first time you saw it, that kind of, you know?

00:52:18.640 --> 00:52:26.640
Well, mostly what I saw, I didn't actually get out into where the, you know, the men worked,

00:52:26.640 --> 00:52:31.640
because actually the office buildings looked quite nice,

00:52:31.640 --> 00:52:40.640
and there were about four separate blocks of offices when I went there,

00:52:40.640 --> 00:52:48.640
and they weren't sort of old, you know, like some of the old, you know, the old sort of stone buildings.

00:52:48.640 --> 00:52:51.640
They weren't like that. They were brick buildings.

00:52:51.640 --> 00:52:56.640
And they were just two floors. You know, they weren't tall buildings.

00:52:56.640 --> 00:53:04.640
But that all looked tidy, and you walked across the yard,

00:53:04.640 --> 00:53:10.640
and the yard was tarmacked. That was fine.

00:53:10.640 --> 00:53:14.640
And then, you know, then you worked a bit further on.

00:53:14.640 --> 00:53:17.640
That was when you started crossing the railway lines,

00:53:17.640 --> 00:53:23.640
and that's when you were getting closer to where all the business end went on.

00:53:23.640 --> 00:53:28.640
And there were two labs. There was the one I was in was the control lab,

00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:35.640
but there was also a fuel lab next door, and they were more or less the same sort of buildings.

00:53:35.640 --> 00:53:41.640
They were just like a square, and they were two stories with flat roofs.

00:53:41.640 --> 00:53:47.640
I did go in the fuel lab once or twice, but not to work.

00:53:47.640 --> 00:53:52.640
I just knew somebody. The chap there was in tech where I was.

00:53:52.640 --> 00:53:55.640
We were doing the same course.

00:53:55.640 --> 00:54:01.640
What was it like then on the factory floor, inside those big sheds?

00:54:01.640 --> 00:54:04.640
It looked dark, and dirty.

00:54:04.640 --> 00:54:08.640
Tell me about when the rods came off, because I think you told me that, didn't you?

00:54:08.640 --> 00:54:15.640
Oh, sorry. I don't know where it came from,

00:54:15.640 --> 00:54:25.640
but this rod, and it was not a thick rod, not sort of two inches diameter or anything like that.

00:54:25.640 --> 00:54:34.640
It came shooting out, and it travelled quite fast on a track, and the steel was red hot.

00:54:34.640 --> 00:54:41.640
And when we were up in the control room, one of the rods came off the track,

00:54:41.640 --> 00:54:47.640
and just went snaking across the factory floor, and everybody just jumped out of the way,

00:54:47.640 --> 00:54:51.640
because you couldn't do anything else.

00:54:51.640 --> 00:54:54.640
That was frightening. I only saw that once. That was enough.

00:54:54.640 --> 00:55:01.640
But I'd heard chaps talk about it happening, you know, and some nasty accidents, I think.

00:55:01.640 --> 00:55:06.640
But I can't remember what.

00:55:06.640 --> 00:55:13.640
In social life, were there any social activities organised by the workers?

00:55:13.640 --> 00:55:22.640
Yes, there was a sports club, Nettlefolds, and I think it was shared with the big steelworks,

00:55:22.640 --> 00:55:29.640
you know, that was alongside St. George Street, and it ran parallel to that.

00:55:29.640 --> 00:55:36.640
They had a lovely sports club down on Sloper Road, and there was quite a bit of ground with it,

00:55:36.640 --> 00:55:39.640
you know, with football, pitches and all the rest of it.

00:55:39.640 --> 00:55:48.640
We often went down there, and we'd challenge another department to play Skittles,

00:55:48.640 --> 00:55:52.640
so we'd just go down and play Skittles and things like that.

00:55:53.640 --> 00:56:00.640
It was a very nice club, yeah, but I think, well, there's houses built there now anyway.

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:03.640
So did you go there quite often?

00:56:03.640 --> 00:56:08.640
No, no, no. I think the only times I went there was when, you know,

00:56:08.640 --> 00:56:12.640
we sort of had a little challenge, Skittles match, that's all.

00:56:12.640 --> 00:56:14.640
Did you have a bar and things like that?

00:56:14.640 --> 00:56:15.640
Yes, yeah.

00:56:15.640 --> 00:56:21.640
What about Christmas activities, Christmas parties and stuff like that?

00:56:21.640 --> 00:56:23.640
They're usually famous.

00:56:24.640 --> 00:56:30.640
They used to have staff dances or dinners and dance down at,

00:56:30.640 --> 00:56:35.640
sometimes they'd have them down at Bindles, down in Barry,

00:56:35.640 --> 00:56:42.640
but they also used to have, I think they had a couple of,

00:56:42.640 --> 00:56:46.640
they used to have some things in the Royal Hotel in Cardiff.

00:56:46.640 --> 00:56:52.640
The meals were always awful, but the dancing was okay.

00:56:54.640 --> 00:56:57.640
No, they used to, and the last day that we worked, you know,

00:56:57.640 --> 00:57:02.640
well, perhaps we'd finish work at 12, it might be Christmas Eve,

00:57:02.640 --> 00:57:06.640
we always had a party in the lab because the time we came out,

00:57:06.640 --> 00:57:08.640
all the buses had gone.

00:57:08.640 --> 00:57:13.640
So we used to hitchhike.

00:57:13.640 --> 00:57:19.640
But there'd be a big group of us and, you know, lots of lorries going past

00:57:19.640 --> 00:57:22.640
and we got into the back of an egg lorry one day,

00:57:22.640 --> 00:57:27.640
but there were a big group of us, you know, it wasn't like hitchhiking on your own.

00:57:28.640 --> 00:57:31.640
So these Christmas parties, I mean these dinners and dances,

00:57:31.640 --> 00:57:33.640
were they always Christmas do's?

00:57:33.640 --> 00:57:35.640
Yes, yes, yes.

00:57:35.640 --> 00:57:49.640
Were they attended by workers or workers and their families or partners or whatever?

00:57:49.640 --> 00:57:58.640
Yeah, there was always, you know, a difference between the workers and the staff,

00:57:58.640 --> 00:58:03.640
because the girls that worked upstairs in the lab, we were staff.

00:58:03.640 --> 00:58:06.640
Most of the men who worked downstairs were works.

00:58:06.640 --> 00:58:13.640
So they would have separate do's for staff and the workers.

00:58:13.640 --> 00:58:16.640
They always had separate evening do's,

00:58:16.640 --> 00:58:21.640
because the works ones would be much bigger because there were lots of,

00:58:21.640 --> 00:58:24.640
you know, there were much more men working out there.

00:58:24.640 --> 00:58:27.640
I assume they took their wives.

00:58:27.640 --> 00:58:38.640
Were there a kind of, did the staff look down on the workers or were you aware of any kind of social hierarchy?

00:58:38.640 --> 00:58:40.640
I don't think so.

00:58:40.640 --> 00:58:44.640
Well, you know, I didn't feel that way because, you know,

00:58:44.640 --> 00:58:48.640
you'd get some of the men from the factory floor coming up for something or other,

00:58:48.640 --> 00:58:54.640
because the chaps who worked, lots of the chaps who worked downstairs preparing all the samples,

00:58:54.640 --> 00:58:57.640
they were works, you know, they weren't staff,

00:58:57.640 --> 00:59:03.640
and you sort of got to know them, you know, say good morning, have a little chat.

00:59:03.640 --> 00:59:06.640
So I didn't feel that way.

00:59:06.640 --> 00:59:09.640
We used to go into the workers' canteen sometimes.

00:59:09.640 --> 00:59:14.640
I think it was if we worked on a weekend, if something had gone wrong,

00:59:14.640 --> 00:59:17.640
because the staff canteen wouldn't be open.

00:59:17.640 --> 00:59:20.640
Why the segregation then, do you think?

00:59:20.640 --> 00:59:23.640
Was it just because of numbers maybe?

00:59:23.640 --> 00:59:25.640
Yeah, maybe.

00:59:25.640 --> 00:59:33.640
I mean, using different buildings may have been because of the workmen in their dirty overalls,

00:59:33.640 --> 00:59:40.640
and then, you know, the sort of, especially lots of the young ladies who worked in the offices,

00:59:40.640 --> 00:59:43.640
they would be very smart.

00:59:43.640 --> 00:59:50.640
And so the works canteen was not really very,

00:59:50.640 --> 00:59:54.640
left a lot to be desired, shall we say.

00:59:54.640 --> 00:59:58.640
But I mean, we used to use it if we were there on weekends,

00:59:58.640 --> 01:00:06.640
because we'd go in and have some chips and not just something to eat.

01:00:06.640 --> 01:00:08.640
How long did you work there?

01:00:08.640 --> 01:00:10.640
Five years altogether.

01:00:10.640 --> 01:00:13.640
And what did you do afterwards?

01:00:13.640 --> 01:00:15.640
I had a break in between.

01:00:15.640 --> 01:00:20.640
I went down to distillers for a couple of years down in Barry, which is BP now.

01:00:20.640 --> 01:00:22.640
Oh, all right.

01:00:22.640 --> 01:00:27.640
They made PVC and resins and things like that.

01:00:27.640 --> 01:00:30.640
How did that compare to GKN?

01:00:30.640 --> 01:00:38.640
Oh, it was a lot different, because the lab I was in there was not a control lab.

01:00:38.640 --> 01:00:41.640
So tell me what the difference is then.

01:00:41.640 --> 01:00:46.640
A control lab is you're just checking everything that's been made

01:00:46.640 --> 01:00:50.640
to make sure it's up to specification.

01:00:50.640 --> 01:00:58.640
Whereas when I went to work in distillers, they were making PVC,

01:00:58.640 --> 01:01:09.640
and we were trying to sort of, we were test to see if we could get it to be useful for some sort of purpose.

01:01:09.640 --> 01:01:13.640
You know, a company would perhaps get in touch with somebody and say,

01:01:13.640 --> 01:01:16.640
look, can you try doing this?

01:01:16.640 --> 01:01:23.640
And I can remember doing something with some product, I can't remember what.

01:01:23.640 --> 01:01:32.640
And what it did was it waterproofed something, so it looked a bit like one of these yellow oil skins.

01:01:32.640 --> 01:01:38.640
And then we tested PVC to use as records, you know, discs.

01:01:38.640 --> 01:01:48.640
And there was actually a machine there that would press a disc, make it, and I had one and I played it for years.

01:01:48.640 --> 01:01:50.640
On PVC?

01:01:50.640 --> 01:01:52.640
Yes, yes, and things like that.

01:01:52.640 --> 01:01:58.640
So it was a, and it wasn't quite so, it wasn't so mucky and dirty.

01:01:58.640 --> 01:02:02.640
There were lots more labs there as well, there were a lot of labs there.

01:02:02.640 --> 01:02:05.640
Were there a lot of women working there?

01:02:05.640 --> 01:02:06.640
Yes.

01:02:06.640 --> 01:02:14.640
And was it the same kind of, did you, you know, what did you prefer, which workplace did you prefer really?

01:02:14.640 --> 01:02:23.640
I think I preferred steelworks because I preferred the work, I think,

01:02:23.640 --> 01:02:29.640
because I preferred to have a structure and something that told me what I had to do

01:02:29.640 --> 01:02:33.640
rather than sort of think, oh, well, I'll try this, or I'll try that.

01:02:33.640 --> 01:02:35.640
I'm not very good at that.

01:02:35.640 --> 01:02:38.640
So I preferred that work.

01:02:38.640 --> 01:02:42.640
What about the camaraderie and the social life?

01:02:42.640 --> 01:02:45.640
Did you make friends down in Distillers as well?

01:02:45.640 --> 01:02:55.640
Yes, yes, yes, and I mean, because it was in Barry, so I know quite a lot of people in Barry as well.

01:02:55.640 --> 01:02:58.640
And there were some real characters work there.

01:02:58.640 --> 01:03:02.640
There were always characters somewhere, wherever you work.

01:03:02.640 --> 01:03:04.640
What about the wages down in Distillers?

01:03:04.640 --> 01:03:07.640
What year were we talking about here?

01:03:07.640 --> 01:03:09.640
When did I go there?

01:03:09.640 --> 01:03:18.640
When I was 19 or 20, so it could have been, it was 1960, 61, something like that.

01:03:18.640 --> 01:03:23.640
And the wages were a bit better, they paid more.

01:03:23.640 --> 01:03:27.640
And then they put us on to monthly pay.

01:03:27.640 --> 01:03:32.640
That absolutely floored me.

01:03:32.640 --> 01:03:40.640
I expect lots of others were the same because you get paid for a month and you think, gosh, I'm rich.

01:03:40.640 --> 01:03:48.640
And for a whole week you have a wonderful time and then you can't afford to go out.

01:03:48.640 --> 01:03:53.640
And I can remember my mother found it difficult.

01:03:53.640 --> 01:03:59.640
And she said to me in the end, she said, I'm sorry, but you'll have to give me money weekly.

01:03:59.640 --> 01:04:04.640
I can't cope with it monthly because she'd always used to handle in money weekly.

01:04:04.640 --> 01:04:06.640
So that's what I did.

01:04:06.640 --> 01:04:10.640
And I still actually budget weekly now.

01:04:10.640 --> 01:04:14.640
How did you get down to Barry?

01:04:14.640 --> 01:04:16.640
I went on the bus.

01:04:16.640 --> 01:04:21.640
And then I did just to get a lift then with the chap who lived in Pensiesley Road.

01:04:21.640 --> 01:04:24.640
I'd catch the bus down to Pensiesley Road.

01:04:25.640 --> 01:04:30.640
I was there in 1963 in the bad winter.

01:04:30.640 --> 01:04:36.640
And it was strange because we got to work.

01:04:36.640 --> 01:04:40.640
People from Barry couldn't get in.

01:04:40.640 --> 01:04:48.640
We always used to say, Barry's like Rome, built on seven hills.

01:04:48.640 --> 01:04:51.640
But everywhere you go in Barry there's a hill.

01:04:51.640 --> 01:04:54.640
So they couldn't get there.

01:04:54.640 --> 01:04:57.640
So how long were you there for?

01:04:57.640 --> 01:04:59.640
Two years I think.

01:04:59.640 --> 01:05:01.640
I went back to the steelworks then.

01:05:01.640 --> 01:05:02.640
Oh did you?

01:05:02.640 --> 01:05:04.640
For a couple of years then.

01:05:04.640 --> 01:05:06.640
And what was that like going back there?

01:05:06.640 --> 01:05:08.640
There were different people there.

01:05:08.640 --> 01:05:12.640
It wasn't such, you know, it was okay.

01:05:12.640 --> 01:05:18.640
But you know, lots of the people who'd been there when I'd worked there before had gone.

01:05:18.640 --> 01:05:22.640
And there were some people there that were a bit more difficult.

01:05:22.640 --> 01:05:25.640
But never mind.

01:05:25.640 --> 01:05:28.640
Then I went to the Ministry of Agriculture.

01:05:28.640 --> 01:05:30.640
And what was that like?

01:05:30.640 --> 01:05:32.640
I loved it.

01:05:32.640 --> 01:05:34.640
That was good.

01:05:34.640 --> 01:05:36.640
Yeah, that was lab work as well.

01:05:36.640 --> 01:05:45.640
That was analysing agricultural materials, soil and feed for sheep and cows and hay.

01:05:45.640 --> 01:05:47.640
And lots of different things.

01:05:47.640 --> 01:05:49.640
And it was only a small place.

01:05:49.640 --> 01:05:51.640
Where was that?

01:05:51.640 --> 01:05:52.640
In Llanisian.

01:05:52.640 --> 01:05:54.640
You know where the tax offices are?

01:05:54.640 --> 01:06:02.640
It was on the site there when the whole area was all single storey buildings.

01:06:02.640 --> 01:06:05.640
And I did enjoy it there.

01:06:05.640 --> 01:06:07.640
I was there for 21 years.

01:06:07.640 --> 01:06:09.640
And then they closed the stand.

01:06:09.640 --> 01:06:15.640
Are you in contact with any of your workmates from the factories?

01:06:15.640 --> 01:06:17.640
Yeah, yeah.

01:06:17.640 --> 01:06:21.640
I spoke to one the other day.

01:06:21.640 --> 01:06:25.640
And I met her for coffee not so long ago.

01:06:25.640 --> 01:06:26.640
And there's another one.

01:06:26.640 --> 01:06:28.640
The three of us were all the same age.

01:06:28.640 --> 01:06:31.640
And you know, we were sort of very friendly.

01:06:31.640 --> 01:06:33.640
And I've seen the other one as well.

01:06:33.640 --> 01:06:36.640
And then I spoke to my friend the other day.

01:06:36.640 --> 01:06:38.640
